A **`.ko`** (kernel object) is compiled kernel code loaded into the running kernel's address space at runtime. Tooling:

```bash
lsmod                      # what's loaded (name, size, use count, dependents)
modinfo i2c_dev            # author, license, params, dependencies, vermagic
sudo insmod ./hello.ko     # raw load, no dep resolution
sudo modprobe i2c_dev      # resolves deps via modules.dep, searches /lib/modules
sudo rmmod hello           # unload (refcount must be 0)
sudo depmod                # rebuild modules.dep after installing modules
```

`modprobe` reads `/etc/modprobe.d/` for **parameters** (`options snd_hda_intel power_save=1`) and **blacklisting** (`blacklist nouveau`). Loading an out-of-tree or proprietary module sets the **taint** flag (see `dmesg`); maintainers ignore bug reports from a tainted kernel. A minimal module:

```c
#include <linux/module.h>
#include <linux/init.h>
static int __init hello_init(void){ printk(KERN_INFO "hello: loaded\n"); return 0; }
static void __exit hello_exit(void){ printk(KERN_INFO "hello: bye\n"); }
module_init(hello_init); module_exit(hello_exit);
MODULE_LICENSE("GPL");
```

Build it against your kernel headers with a one-line Makefile (`obj-m += hello.o`) and `make -C /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build M=$PWD`, then `insmod` and read `dmesg`. Promote it to a **character driver**: define a `file_operations` struct (`.read`, `.write`, `.open`), then register either the old `register_chrdev()` or the modern **`cdev`** pair `alloc_chrdev_region()` + `cdev_init()` + `cdev_add()`:

```c
static struct file_operations fops = { .owner=THIS_MODULE, .read=my_read, .write=my_write };
```

For real hardware you go further: a **platform driver** matched to a node in the **device tree** (`of_match_table`) on its `compatible` string, then `ioremap()` the **MMIO** registers and `request_irq()` for interrupts -- exactly the radar/register-poking model, now inside the kernel. This connects directly to the embedded module later.

The **device tree (DT)** exists to solve one problem: most SoC peripherals are **not discoverable**. A USB or PCIe device can announce its vendor/product IDs, but an I2C temperature sensor wired to pins on your custom board cannot. Rather than hardcode every board into the kernel (the bad old ARM 'board files' era), Linux passes the kernel a **device tree blob (DTB)** describing the hardware as a tree of **nodes** and **properties**.

You write **`.dts`** source (and shared **`.dtsi`** include files for the SoC, included by board files) and compile it with the device-tree compiler **`dtc`** into a `.dtb`:

```dts
/dts-v1/;
#include "my-soc.dtsi"

&i2c1 {
    status = "okay";
    bmp280@76 {
        compatible = "bosch,bmp280";
        reg = <0x76>;        /* I2C address */
    };
};
```

The load-bearing property is **`compatible`**. The kernel matches a node's `compatible` string against each driver's `of_device_id` table; on a match the driver's `probe()` runs and binds to that node (this is exactly the platform/OF device model from Module 9). **A typo in the `compatible` string means no match, no probe, and a silent non-working peripheral** — the single most common DT bug.

```bash
dtc -I dts -O dtb -o board.dtb board.dts   # compile source to blob
dtc -I dtb -O dts -o out.dts board.dtb     # decompile to inspect
```

**Device-tree overlays** let you patch the base tree at runtime (e.g., enabling SPI or a GPIO LED on a Raspberry Pi) without recompiling the whole DTB — ideal for experimentation. Cardinal rule: edit the `.dts`, recompile, and redeploy the DTB. Never hand-edit the binary `.dtb`, and never forget to redeploy it after a change.
